    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-06-19T17:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-06-19T17:30:00-05:00" n="771"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d771">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">821.20/293: Airgram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Colombia</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Daniels</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-06-19T18:30:00-04:00"
                            >June 19, 1944—6:30 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>A–434. Your 706 of April 14.<note n="20" xml:id="d771fn20">Not printed.</note>
                    The Department has received a letter from the Secretary of War<note n="21"
                        xml:id="d771fn21">Henry L. Stimson.</note> with reference to training of
                    Colombian Army Aviators for combat duty stating that views transmitted in War
                    Department’s letter of May 22 (see Department’s A–417 of June 13<note n="22"
                        xml:id="d771fn22">Not printed; it quoted the War Department’s letter of May
                        22, 1944, which indicated that the disadvantages of arranging for 300
                        Colombians to serve actively in the war outweighed the advantages
                        (821.20/293).</note>) are also applicable to the employment of small groups
                    of aviators from any of the American Republics. War Department adds however that
                    in appreciation of the beneficial effect which such cooperation would have on
                    our relations with these countries, it is now investigating the feasibility of
                    establishing a special training program whereby courses of instruction in
                    appropriate phases of military activity would be offered to the military
                    personnel from such countries.</p>
                <p>War Department has informally stated that such a program, even if found to be
                    feasible, would not make it possible to utilize the trained men in active
                    theaters.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>[<hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
